  <h1>Using it as a library</h1>
  <p class="docs-sub">The proxy engine is a separate crate, <code>torana-core</code>, with none of the standalone binary's listener/signal machinery.</p>

  <p>Embed it inside a hyper server you already run instead of running torana as a separate process:</p>

  <CodeBlock
    label="embed ProxyEngine"
    copy={'use torana_core::{Config, ProxyEngine, Metrics};\nuse std::sync::Arc;\n\nlet engine = ProxyEngine::new(config, Arc::new(metrics));\nengine.spawn_health_probers().await;\n\n// inside your own service_fn:\nlet response = engine.handle(req, client_addr, "http").await?;'}
  ><Fragment set:html={`use torana_core::{Config, ProxyEngine, Metrics};
use std::sync::Arc;

let engine = ProxyEngine::new(config, Arc::new(metrics));
engine.spawn_health_probers().await;

<span class="cm">// inside your own service_fn:</span>
let response = engine.handle(req, client_addr, <span class="ac">"http"</span>).await?;`} /></CodeBlock>

  <p><code>Server</code> (what the <code>torana</code> binary uses) is a thin wrapper around <code>ProxyEngine</code> that adds listener binding, SIGHUP reload, and graceful shutdown on top — read <code>torana-core/src/server.rs</code> if you want that full behavior instead of wiring it up yourself.</p>

  <p>Next: <a href="../signals/">signals &amp; reloads</a>.</p>
</DocsLayout>
